A "'''soft target'''" is "a person or thing that is relatively unprotected or vulnerable, especially to military or [[terrorist attack]]."{{Sfn|Oxford Dictionaries Online||}}
==Etymology==
The terms "soft target" and "hard target" are flexible in nature and the distinction between the two is not always clear.{{Sfn|Forest|2006|p=38}} However, typical "soft targets" are civilian sites where unarmed people congregate in large numbers; examples include [[national monument]]s, hospitals, schools, sporting arenas, hotels, cultural centers,  movie theaters, [[café]]s and restaurants, [[places of worship]], nightclubs, shopping centers, transportation sites (such as [[railway station]]s, buses, rail systems, and ferries), and farmers' cooperatives.{{Sfn|Forest|2006|p=37}}{{Sfn|McGovern|2012|p=371}}{{Sfn|Bennett|2007|p=62}}{{Sfn|Preston|1987|}} Soft targets are contrasted with hard targets, which typically restrict access to the public and are well-protected.{{Sfn|Bennett|2007|p=62}} Examples of hard targets include airports, government buildings, military installations, [[diplomatic missions]], and [[power station]]s.{{Sfn|Forest|2006|p=37}}{{Sfn|McGovern|2012|p=371}}{{Sfn|Bennett|2007|p=62}}

==History==
Terrorist groups almost exclusively choose to strike soft targets.{{Sfn|McGovern|2012|p=371}}{{Sfn|Forest|2006|p=40}} Of terrorist attacks worldwide from 1968 to 2005, 72% (8,111) struck soft targets and 27% (4,248) struck hard targets.{{Sfn|Forest|2006|pp=39-40}} The intent of attacks on soft targets is to instil fear as well as inflict casualties.{{Sfn|Bennett|2007|p=62}} [[Clark Kent Ervin]] notes that attacks on soft targets inflict psychological damage.{{Sfn|Ervin|2006|p=158}} In 2011, while preparations were being made for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], the deputy commissioner of London's [[Metropolitan Police Service]] noted that if the primary targets were secure, terrorists might substitute targets that are nearby but not as well protected.{{Sfn|Ervin|2006|p=103}}

Military and paramilitary groups may adopt a strategy of attacking soft targets in order to avoid direct confrontation with a stronger opponent. For example, U.S. military general [[John Galvin (general)|John Galvin]] noted in 1987 that [[Contras|Contra rebels]] switched to civilian targets rather than continuing the direct fighting against the [[Sandinista National Liberation Front]].{{Sfn|Kaplan|1987|}}

